      </div>
      <p class="MsoNormal">
        <br clear="all" style="mso-special-character:line-break;page-break-before:always"/>
      </p>
      <div class="Section3">
        <a name="_f15b17ef-6427-0cf7-e8b8-1adda2ecb97c" id="_f15b17ef-6427-0cf7-e8b8-1adda2ecb97c"></a>
        <h1 class="Annex"><b>Annex B</b><br/>(informative)<br/><b>Relationship with OGC Features and Observations</b></h1>
        <p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_7be84c96-2569-7cd9-97df-f86edce8e9b3" id="_7be84c96-2569-7cd9-97df-f86edce8e9b3"></a>EmissionML is a domain-specific conceptual model that builds on two foundational OGC concepts: <b>Features</b> (ISO 19109 General Feature Model) and <b>Observations</b> (ISO/OGC 19156:2023, OMS 3.0). This annex explains how EmissionML relates to each and why explicit domain modeling is preferred over generic usage.</p>
        <p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_3563a859-b3ee-95a9-3165-7709bda45bb8" id="_3563a859-b3ee-95a9-3165-7709bda45bb8"></a><a href="#fig-annex-b-layering">Figure B.1</a> illustrates the conceptual layering of EmissionML on top of these foundational standards.</p>
        <div class="figure"><a name="fig-annex-b-layering" id="fig-annex-b-layering"></a>

<p class="figure" style="page-break-after:avoid;"><img src="cid:6a349f56-5379-4544-b8c3-3a848511514d.png" height="225" width="489"/></p><p class="FigureTitle" style="text-align:center;">Figure B.1&#xA0;&#x2014; Conceptual layering of EmissionML on foundational ISO/OGC standards</p></div>
        <div><a name="_a3aa9728-f71c-63ef-ec3e-dee75f02a6e1" id="_a3aa9728-f71c-63ef-ec3e-dee75f02a6e1"></a><h2>B.1.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OGC Features</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_727fe038-b3c6-d852-8dde-578808e54ca2" id="_727fe038-b3c6-d852-8dde-578808e54ca2"></a>The OGC General Feature Model (ISO 19109) defines a <i>Feature</i> as an abstraction of a real-world phenomenon &#x2014; any entity with an identity, properties, and optionally a geometry. EmissionML makes this alignment explicit by introducing a concrete <b>Feature</b> class (stereotyped <tt>&lt;&lt;ISO 19109&gt;&gt;</tt>) into the conceptual model.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_901c8f69-c3de-dd92-0711-c26556b11e0c" id="_901c8f69-c3de-dd92-0711-c26556b11e0c"></a>The Feature class carries a mandatory <tt>geometry</tt> attribute of type <tt>GM_Object</tt> and serves as the base class for domain-specific feature types. <b>Source</b> inherits from Feature, gaining its geometry by inheritance. This structural inheritance &#x2014; rather than a notional stereotype &#x2014; makes the ISO 19109 alignment unambiguous and machine-verifiable.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_88960b56-c502-f126-c603-02b1e239edb1" id="_88960b56-c502-f126-c603-02b1e239edb1"></a>Because Feature is concrete, an Observation&#x2019;s <tt>ultimateFeatureOfInterest</tt> can reference any Feature &#x2014; not only a Source. This enables observations whose feature of interest is defined at a different spatial scale (e.g., a facility area, a region, or a monitoring zone) to participate in the evidence chain without being forced into the Source class.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_479f70ea-1139-221f-6c17-2a861fdf858e" id="_479f70ea-1139-221f-6c17-2a861fdf858e"></a><b>EmissionEvent</b> is also a real-world phenomenon &#x2014; an occurrent that unfolds over time. In principle, an Emission Event <i>could</i> be modeled as a generic Feature. However, EmissionML gives it explicit structure: temporal bounds (start time, end time), a quantity of emitted substance, a mechanism describing the physical or operational process, an intent classification, and an evidence chain linking the event to supporting Observations.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_e2f8fbf1-3f1b-af7d-4166-11632416d995" id="_e2f8fbf1-3f1b-af7d-4166-11632416d995"></a>Without this explicit modeling, a Source would be indistinguishable from any other Feature, and an emission event would be &#x201C;just another Feature&#x201D; with ad-hoc properties. The semantic relationships that give emission data its meaning &#x2014; <tt>hasSource</tt>, <tt>hasMechanism</tt>, <tt>hasQuantity</tt>, <tt>hasStartTimeEvidence</tt> &#x2014; would be lost or require convention-based interpretation.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_6667b66f-06f6-9fc3-6211-c94224d416e3" id="_6667b66f-06f6-9fc3-6211-c94224d416e3"></a><h2>B.2.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OMS 3.0 Observations</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_0ce15fd6-6e9d-6e33-1682-cffaad51f1a4" id="_0ce15fd6-6e9d-6e33-1682-cffaad51f1a4"></a>OMS 3.0 (ISO/OGC 19156:2023) defines an Observation as an act of determining the value of an observable property. An Observation has a well-defined structure: a feature of interest, an observed property, a procedure, and a result.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_9523e135-f0c9-7442-772d-81265784dfcc" id="_9523e135-f0c9-7442-772d-81265784dfcc"></a>EmissionML incorporates OMS 3.0 Observation <b>by reference</b> (Requirement 8) &#x2014; it does not redefine or extend the Observation class. In EmissionML, Observations serve as <b>evidence</b> supporting emission quantity and temporal bound determinations, linked through the <tt>hasQuantityEvidence</tt>, <tt>hasStartTimeEvidence</tt>, and <tt>hasEndTimeEvidence</tt> associations.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_242d33f1-bdfe-4337-3d94-d9aba9e1bbef" id="_242d33f1-bdfe-4337-3d94-d9aba9e1bbef"></a>One might ask: <i>Why not model the entire emission event as an Observation result?</i> Because an Emission Event is richer than what a single Observation captures. An Emission Event has a source, a mechanism, an intent, multiple temporal bounds, and can be supported by <i>multiple</i> Observations at different spatial and temporal scales. For example:</p>

<div class="ul_wrap"><p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo4;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst"><a name="_3d69b7fa-ed1b-3b4c-89e5-a5aa7cfee479" id="_3d69b7fa-ed1b-3b4c-89e5-a5aa7cfee479"></a>A satellite remote sensing Observation may detect a methane plume over a broad area.
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo4;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_60d93f1e-4cf0-d552-4482-2e0dd374a1e1" id="_60d93f1e-4cf0-d552-4482-2e0dd374a1e1"></a>An Optical Gas Imaging (OGI) camera Observation may pinpoint the leak to a specific component.
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo4;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast"><a name="_4d3edf11-1f4e-f79d-15e0-36de173ff829" id="_4d3edf11-1f4e-f79d-15e0-36de173ff829"></a>A continuous emissions monitoring system (CEMS) Observation may quantify the emission rate over time.
</p>
</div>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_e101de3a-ebe8-54c0-0a4a-79de265c6a02" id="_e101de3a-ebe8-54c0-0a4a-79de265c6a02"></a>All three Observations can serve as evidence for a single Emission Event, each contributing to the determination of quantity, start time, or end time. The Observation&#x2019;s <tt>ultimateFeatureOfInterest</tt> references a Feature &#x2014; which may be a Source or any other Feature at a different spatial scale. The satellite Observation&#x2019;s feature of interest may be a Feature representing an entire facility, while the OGI Observation&#x2019;s feature of interest is a Source representing a single valve.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_c3f78d6c-ca6d-dd89-6bcd-be4e9cb97dd6" id="_c3f78d6c-ca6d-dd89-6bcd-be4e9cb97dd6"></a><h2>B.3.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>EmissionML and OMS 3.0 Procedures</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_5c132e70-9890-3239-eb91-45ee55a8cddc" id="_5c132e70-9890-3239-eb91-45ee55a8cddc"></a>OMS 3.0 defines a <b>Procedure</b> as &#x201C;a description of steps performed&#x201D; and introduces <b>ObservingProcedure</b> as a specialization that describes steps performed to determine the value of an observable property. EmissionML follows this same specialization pattern.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_480f5fd9-983d-f585-52ae-e9360b92383d" id="_480f5fd9-983d-f585-52ae-e9360b92383d"></a>The EmissionML conceptual model introduces a <b>Procedure</b> class (stereotyped <tt>&lt;&lt;ISO 19156:2023&gt;&gt;</tt>) as the base class for process descriptions. <b>DeterminationProcedure</b> inherits from Procedure and describes the steps performed to determine a value &#x2014; such as an emission quantity or temporal bound. This structural inheritance mirrors how ObservingProcedure specializes Procedure in OMS 3.0.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_739aafb1-f978-d834-b7b9-e79c514817d2" id="_739aafb1-f978-d834-b7b9-e79c514817d2"></a>By making Procedure an explicit base class rather than a notional reference, EmissionML ensures that its process descriptions are structurally aligned with OMS 3.0 &#x2014; not merely by naming convention, but by class hierarchy. This parallels the Feature/Source pattern: just as Source inherits from Feature to make ISO 19109 alignment concrete, DeterminationProcedure inherits from Procedure to make OMS 3.0 alignment concrete.</p>
</div>
        <div><a name="_71435721-078d-e5a8-ceb7-36648dc95164" id="_71435721-078d-e5a8-ceb7-36648dc95164"></a><h2>B.4.<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span>Why Explicit Domain Modeling</h2>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_cceefffb-a26f-e5c2-963d-d3e150e7cbba" id="_cceefffb-a26f-e5c2-963d-d3e150e7cbba"></a><b>The alternative.</b> One could model everything with generic Features and Observations &#x2014; Sources as plain Features, emission data as Observation results, and relationships as ad-hoc properties. This approach uses only existing OGC standards without defining new classes.</p>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_2db412e0-1ff0-422d-4cf5-63aea48fbcef" id="_2db412e0-1ff0-422d-4cf5-63aea48fbcef"></a><b>The problem.</b> Generic modeling loses domain semantics. Without EmissionML&#x2019;s explicit classes, systems cannot:</p>

<div class="ul_wrap"><p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo5;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst"><a name="_963bf8ea-c04f-40dd-b305-331fc9e5dab9" id="_963bf8ea-c04f-40dd-b305-331fc9e5dab9"></a>distinguish a Source from any other Feature,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo5;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_c90de1ee-671c-b8c5-6f5e-6b2bad47d8c5" id="_c90de1ee-671c-b8c5-6f5e-6b2bad47d8c5"></a>enforce that an emission has a Mechanism and an Intent,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo5;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle"><a name="_1e83e964-ca19-60bf-660a-9f88fea3a21b" id="_1e83e964-ca19-60bf-660a-9f88fea3a21b"></a>trace the evidence chain from Observation to Emission Quantity to Emission Event,
</p>
<p style="mso-list:l3 level1 lfo5;" class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast"><a name="_f18d42de-a10e-fc62-70d6-7420ba0c3739" id="_f18d42de-a10e-fc62-70d6-7420ba0c3739"></a>validate that required relationships are present (e.g., every Emission Event must have a Source, a Mechanism, and a Determination Procedure).
</p>
</div>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_039319c2-b901-1b83-b46d-099d09017039" id="_039319c2-b901-1b83-b46d-099d09017039"></a><b>What explicit modeling provides:</b></p>

<table class="dl"><a name="_a04e75fc-27aa-eb63-69fc-4ef460538af5" id="_a04e75fc-27aa-eb63-69fc-4ef460538af5"></a><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Interoperability</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_535d3ed3-ec84-f6ce-b753-27398c505006" id="_535d3ed3-ec84-f6ce-b753-27398c505006"></a>Systems exchanging EmissionML data share a common vocabulary. EmissionEvent, Source, Mechanism, and EmissionQuantity are unambiguous &#x2014; they mean the same thing in every implementation.</p>
</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Validation</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_a9f435d5-7ecf-46d8-8cb7-a8e047284789" id="_a9f435d5-7ecf-46d8-8cb7-a8e047284789"></a>Requirements can be formally specified and enforced. For example, Requirement 1 mandates that every Emission Event has a Source, a Mechanism, start time, quantity, and their corresponding Determination Procedures.</p>
</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" align="left"><p align="left" style="margin-left:0pt;text-align:left;" class="MsoNormal">Usability</p></td><td valign="top"><p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_03da84ac-81ba-f760-9f71-9bc7e39fc1fd" id="_03da84ac-81ba-f760-9f71-9bc7e39fc1fd"></a>Domain experts work with emission concepts directly &#x2014; <i>emission events</i>, <i>sources</i>, <i>mechanisms</i> &#x2014; rather than mapping to and from generic abstractions. This reduces the cognitive burden and the risk of misinterpretation.</p>
</td></tr></table>

<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="_4712f037-af6f-e042-2a85-fa0ab40dcbaf" id="_4712f037-af6f-e042-2a85-fa0ab40dcbaf"></a><b>Analogy.</b> Just as CityGML defines explicit Building, Road, and Vegetation classes rather than using generic Features, EmissionML defines explicit emission domain classes. The General Feature Model provides the abstract foundation; EmissionML provides the domain-specific vocabulary that makes emission data interoperable and actionable.</p>
</div>
      </div>
      <p class="MsoNormal">
        <br clear="all" style="mso-special-character:line-break;page-break-before:always"/>
      </p>
      <div class="Section3">
        <a name="_1be717d2-8f9e-cea2-3386-1108e1685c03" id="_1be717d2-8f9e-cea2-3386-1108e1685c03"></a>
        <h1 class="Annex"><b>Annex C</b><br/>(informative)<br/><b>Bibliography</b></h1>
        <div>

<div class="Note"><a name="_63d58a6d-50cb-9402-4936-3546814fec14" id="_63d58a6d-50cb-9402-4936-3546814fec14"></a><p class="Note"><span class="note_label">NOTE:<span style="mso-tab-count:1">&#xA0; </span></span>The TC has approved Springer LNCS as the official document citation type.</p><p class="Note"><a name="_b9e0999f-fd85-9ab5-f5a0-70481ae05e2e" id="_b9e0999f-fd85-9ab5-f5a0-70481ae05e2e"></a>Springer LNCS is widely used in technical and computer science journals and other publications</p><p class="Note"><a name="_60dbba11-97e4-ffc3-0891-e0e5c7ac5991" id="_60dbba11-97e4-ffc3-0891-e0e5c7ac5991"></a>&#x2013; Actual References:</p><p class="Note"><a name="_a75e170f-ebc1-1729-b034-013fabe123f9" id="_a75e170f-ebc1-1729-b034-013fabe123f9"></a>[n] Journal: Author Surname, A.: Title. Publication Title. Volume number, Issue number, Pages Used (Year Published)</p></div>



<p class="MsoNormal"><a name="OGC2015" id="OGC2015"></a>[1] OGC: OGC Testbed 12 Annex B: Architecture. (2015).</p>
</div>
      </div>
